    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-11-24T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-11-24T05:00:00-05:00" n="383"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d383">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151/971: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-11-24T17:00:00+07:00"
                            >November 24, 1943—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 26—2:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2231. To Secretary of the Treasury from Adler. Raised question with Dr. Kung in
                    accordance with your instructions in conversation yesterday. He replied that
                    missionaries had been receiving 30 to 1 for missionary expenditures since May 1
                    and that all famine relief expenditures had been receiving 40 to 1 from same
                    date. He was in <pb facs="0465" n="455" xml:id="pg_455"/> course of negotiating
                    with foreign missionary philanthropic and cultural organizations about further
                    adjustment in rate they receive (re your 1474, October 13).</p>
                <p>Above confirmed by reliable source according to which missionaries had been
                    receiving 40 for famine relief expenditures. According to same source, Dr. Kung
                    will probably give above organizations 40 for all their expenditures in China.
                    [Adler.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
